<article>
    <h1>Take your fit&#xAD;ness level up a notch: Are you game?</h1>
    <h2>Learn more about the Lu&#xAD;miHealth app and how mak&#xAD;ing pos&#xAD;i&#xAD;tive life&#xAD;style changes can be fun and re&#xAD;ward&#xAD;ing</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201125/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-25"><time>2020-11-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | LIVING WELL</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHOTO : Gettyimage&#xAD;s</span>
    </section>

    <p>When I re­ceived the chance to do a first-per­son piece on the Lu­miHealth app, I was thrilled. For weeks, I had been hear­ing about this much-dis­cussed col­lab­o­ra­tion be­tween the Health Pro­mo­tion Board (HPB) and Ap­ple, and here was my chance to ex­pe­ri­ence it for my­self.</p>
    <p>This first-of-its-kind app was de­signed in col­lab­o­ra­tion with physi­cians and pub­lic health ex­perts at Ap­ple and HPB. It draws on tech­nol­ogy and be­havioural in­sights to en­cour­age Sin­ga­pore­ans to keep healthy, and com­plete well­ness chal­lenges through their Ap­ple Watch or iPhone.</p>
    <p>What is even more in­ter­est­ing about this app is that apart from its eye-catch­ing game visu­als, it also high­lights im­por­tant health is­sues rel­e­vant to Sin­ga­pore­ans such as di­a­betes and the preven­tion of falls among our se­niors. App users also stand a chance to earn up to $380 in HPB e-vouch­ers, which are re­deemable at Cold Stor­age su­per­mar­ket and Tangs de­part­ment store.</p>

    <div>
